V'''Paolo da Pergola'''<ref>Paolo della Pergola, Paul of Pergula, Paul of Pergola, Paulus Pergulensis or Pergolensis, Paulus de Pergula</ref> (died 1455, in Venice) was an Italian humanist philosopher, mathematician and [[William of Ockham|Occamist]]<ref>Ennio De Bellis, ''[http://books.google.gr/books?id=xgwFAQAAIAAJ&q=Paolo+da+Pergola+vernia&dq= Nicoletto Vernia e Agostino Nifo: aspetti storiografici e metodologici]'', Congedo, 2003, p. 9.</ref> logician. He was a pupil of [[Paul of Venice]].<ref>[http://www.textmanuscripts.com/home/archives/archivesdescription.php?m=107]: ''He became the first publicly paid lecturer in philosophy in Venice, where he was officially honored in a public ceremony. In 1448, he was offered a bishopric, which he refused, and at the end of his life he accepted the administration of the Church of Saint John Almoner.''</ref>\u000a\u000aHis most important work was probably ''De sensu composito et diviso''.<ref>Printed by 1494; it shares a title with a work of [[William of Heytesbury]].</ref> His logical works were printed early.<ref>''Compendium logicae'' printed by [[Erhard Ratdolt]] in 1481; later in Venice as ''Compendium logicae; De sensu composito et diviso'' (1498); as ''Logica Magistri Pauli Pergolensis''. 1510.[http://edit16.iccu.sbn.it/scripts/iccu_ext.dll?fn=10&i=36208] His ''Dubia'' was printed in 1477.</ref>\u000a\u000aHe taught at the Scuola di Rialto from 1421 to 1454.<ref>[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:vz3olOZn-Z4J:www.unive.it/media/allegato/download/Lettere/Materiale_didattico_Caracciolo/0607_cult_civilta_umanesimo_rinascimento/lineamenti_cult_civ_umanesimo_rinascim-parte2.pdf](PDF), note p.7 (in Italian).</ref> He was teacher and friend of the glassmaker [[Antonio Barovier]].<ref>[http://www.wga.hu/bio_m/b/barovier/biograph.html PDF].</ref>\u000a\u000aAmong his pupils was also [[Nicoletto Vernia]], a well known professor of philosophy in Padua.<ref>[[Avery Dulles|Avery Robert Dulles]], ''[http://books.google.gr/books?id=McYzAAAAMAAJ&q=Paolo+da+Pergola+vernia&dq= Princeps Concordiae: Pico della Mirandola and the scholastic tradition]'', Harvard University Press, 1941, p. 29.</ref>\u000a\u000aThere is a memorial to him in [[San Giovanni Elemosinario]], Venice.<ref>[http://www.chorusvenezia.org/museo/elemos/2d/giovanni.htm San Giovanni Elemosinario<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\u000a\u000a== Works ==\u000a* ''Logica; and, Tractatus de sensu composito et diviso'' by Paolo della Pergola, edited by Mary Anthony Brown, Saint Bonaventure, New York: Franciscan Institute, 1961.\u000a\u000a==Notes==\u000a{{reflist}}\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Pergola, Paola da}}\u000a[[Category:1455 deaths]]\u000a[[Category:Italian philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Scholastic philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Italian logicians]]\u000a[[Category:Italian Renaissance humanists]]\u000a[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]
